725479f-b.text:
Fifty-seventh Ave., north side, just east of Fifty-eighth Street showing what is said to be the summer home of Gov. De Witt Clinton. In the foreground is the Long Island Railroad tracks parallel with 56th Road. This house was said to have had an extension thereon at one time. The owners or occupants of this house in their order are; Judge Joseph Sackett who erected this house in 1725; Walter Franklin 1796; Col. Isaac Corsa; then Gov. De Witt Clinton; Judge David S. Jones 1842 (he was the Governor's son-in-law); E. Godfrey 1852-1860; and F. Grassy from 1873 to 1909. It was demolished by fire in November 1933.  This is a set of four views.
January 1924.
Views 2 and 3: 1922.
View 4: 1929.
Eugene L. Armbuster Collection.

725491f-a.text:
58th Street, east side, between 57th Road and 57th Drive, showing in a set of four views the Episcopal Church of St. Saviours. This church was erected on land donated by James Maurice in 1840. lIts cornerstone was laid by Bishop Potter on November 1, 1847 and the edifice concentrated on January 28, 1848.
Views 3 and 4 look northward from 57th Drive.
1922.
Views 2 & 4: March 1925.
View 3: January 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

57th Avenue, just east of 58th Street, showing the Sackett homestead, built about 1700 by Joseph Sacket. It is best known as the country home of Governor DeWitt Clinton. It was a1so the home of Walter Franklin, a prominent New York
merchant.
